g to occur that's concrete and palpable, and I do n't know what it's going to be. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s board of directors last week advised the company's shareholders to reject <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>'s second cash tender offer, which totals about $ 1.42 billion, or $ 35 a share In composite trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> closed up 50 cents at $ 38.75 Monday. Analysts have said <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> has a fair market value of about $ 40 a share. London-based <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s second-largest sugar refiner, owns about 5 percent of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s stock and wants to acquire the entire company for its A.E. <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, which produces corn sweeteners. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> was based in <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, until about three years ago, when it moved its headquarters to the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburbs. The British company has promised to move <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s headquarters back to <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> if its takeover attempt succeeds.
